1 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3-3-601 of Title 27A, unless
3 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 This act shall be known and may be cited as the "Urban
5 Agriculture Cost Share Program".
6 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
7 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3-3-602 of Title 27A, unless
8 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
9 A. The Oklahoma Conservation Commission is hereby authorized to
10 establish and administer an Urban Agriculture Cost Share Program as
11 funds become available. The Cost Share Program shall provide monies
12 to eligible persons.
13 B. The purpose of the Urban Agriculture Cost Share Program is
14 to promote sustainable urban agricultural practices, improve food
15 security, and enhance green spaces in Oklahoma's urban areas.
16 C. The Oklahoma Conservation Commission Infrastructure
17 Revolving Fund shall provide funding for the Urban Agriculture Cost
18 Share Program. When sufficient funds are available in the Oklahoma
19 Conservation Commission Infrastructure Revolving Fund, the
20 Commission shall develop and disseminate the program guidelines to
21 the conservation districts containing urban areas. The guidelines
22 shall detail incentives to eligible persons for initiating and
23 continuing urban agriculture initiatives.
24
Req. No. 12577 Page 2

1 D. To implement the program, the Commission shall require
2 conservation districts to enter into contracts for eligible projects
3 on eligible land detailing the eligible person's responsibilities.
4 E. For purposes of the Urban Agriculture Cost Share Program:
5 1. "Eligible person" means any individual, partnership,
6 corporation, or legally recognized Indian tribe which shall include
7 land held in trust, estate, or trust who as an owner, lessee,
8 tenant, or operator participates in the care or management of land
9 within a conservation district;
10 2. "Eligible land" means land that is within five (5) miles of
11 an urban area that is:
12 a. privately owned land within the state,
13 b. land owned by the state or a political subdivision of
14 the state, or
15 c. lands temporarily owned by the United States or a
16 corporation wholly owned by it, which were not
17 acquired or reserved for conservation purposes,
18 including lands administered by the Farm Service
19 Agency, the U.S. Department of Defense, or by any
20 other government agency;
21 3. "Eligible projects" means urban agriculture projects that
22 include, but are not limited to:
23 a. establishing or expanding community gardens in urban
24 neighborhoods,
Req. No. 12577 Page 3

1 b. rooftop and vertical farming,
2 c. installing greenhouses, high tunnels, or hoop houses
3 for food production,
4 d. installing rainwater harvesting systems and efficient
5 irrigation for urban farming,
6 e. enhancing soil health through composting and nutrient
7 management in urban areas,
8 f. establishing urban apiaries,
9 g. planting urban pollinator gardens,
10 h. building livestock infrastructure such as chicken
11 coops or goat enclosures,
12 i. developing and implementing education programs on
13 urban farming practices,
14 j. creating, operating, and maintaining an urban food
15 waste composting program,
16 k. urban marketing initiatives for Oklahoma farms to sell
17 in urban areas,
18 l. other projects that accomplish the objectives and
19 purpose of this Cost Share Program;
20 4. "Urban Area" means the areas in Oklahoma which have been
21 defined by the United States Census Bureau as urban areas based on
22 certain criteria and utilizing data from the most recent Federal
23 Decennial Census.
